---
import { Code } from "astro:components";
import { Button } from "@/components/ui/button";
import { Section } from "@/components/ui/section";
import { Animate } from "@/components/ui/animate";
import { Card } from "@/components/ui/card";
import { EyebrowLabel } from "@/components/ui/eyebrow-label";
import SectionHeading from "@/components/ui/section-heading.astro";
import { CircleArrowRight } from "lucide-react";
---

<Section id="tutorials" size="fit" variant="dark">
  <SectionHeading title="Tutorials" />

  <div class="py-16">
    <div class="container">
      <!-- Tutorial 1: Shiny Acceptance TDD -->
      <div class="pb-16">
        <Animate>
          <div class="flex items-start gap-6">
            <div>
              <a
                href="https://github.com/jakubsob/shiny-acceptance-tdd"
                class="hover:underline"
              >
                <h3 class="text-clamp-sm uppercase leading-none">
                  Shiny Acceptance TDD
                </h3>
              </a>
              <p class="text-muted-foreground mt-3 max-w-[55ch]">
                Build Shiny apps from the outside in. Write acceptance tests
                first, then let them drive every design decision down to the
                module level.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </Animate>
      </div>

      <div>
        <Animate>
          <div
            class="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-[1fr_2fr] gap-8 lg:gap-16 items-start py-16 border-b border-foreground/10"
          >
            <div>
              <EyebrowLabel>
                <span class="text-destructive mr-1">✗</span>vague requirements
              </EyebrowLabel>
              <p
                class="text-sm text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed max-w-[36ch]"
              >
                Stories written in prose stay prose. They can't be run, so
                nobody knows when the app actually satisfies them. Requirements
                drift the moment code ships.
              </p>
            </div>
            <Card variant="destructive">
              <Code
                themes={{ light: "github-light", dark: "github-dark" }}
                lang="text"
                code={`Budget tracking
  As a user I want to see my net balance
  so that I can understand my financial situation.

  Acceptance: shows income, expenses, and net.
  // ← lives in a doc, never executed`}
              />
            </Card>
          </div>
        </Animate>

        <Animate>
          <div
            class="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-[1fr_2fr] gap-8 lg:gap-16 items-start py-16 border-b border-foreground/10"
          >
            <div>
              <EyebrowLabel>
                <span class="text-success mr-1">✓</span>executable specification
              </EyebrowLabel>
              <p
                class="text-sm text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed max-w-[36ch]"
              >
                The same scenario becomes a test. Given-When-Then forces you to
                name preconditions, actions, and outcomes. When it passes, the
                feature is done.
              </p>
            </div>
            <Card variant="success">
              <Code
                themes={{ light: "github-light", dark: "github-dark" }}
                lang="r"
                code={`# tests/acceptance/test-budget.R
test_that("Scenario: I can inspect my net balance", {
  # Given
  dsl$record_income(2000)
  dsl$record_expense(500)
  # When
  dsl$inspect_finances()
  # Then
  dsl$verify_total_income(2000)
  dsl$verify_total_expenses(500)
  dsl$verify_net_balance(1500)
  dsl$teardown()
})`}
              />
            </Card>
          </div>
        </Animate>

        <Animate>
          <div
            class="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-[1fr_2fr] gap-8 lg:gap-16 items-start py-16"
          >
            <div>
              <EyebrowLabel>what you'll learn</EyebrowLabel>
              <ul
                class="text-sm text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed space-y-2 max-w-[36ch]"
              >
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                  <span class="text-success shrink-0">✓</span>Transform user
                  stories into runnable tests
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                  <span class="text-success shrink-0">✓</span>Build a DSL that
                  hides UI details from specs
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                  <span class="text-success shrink-0">✓</span>Keep tests green
                  as the UI evolves
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                  <span class="text-success shrink-0">✓</span>Structure Shiny
                  modules for testability
                </li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
        </Animate>
      </div>

      <div class="text-center pt-8 pb-8">
        <a
          href="https://github.com/jakubsob/shiny-acceptance-tdd"
          target="_blank"
        >
          <Button
            size="xl"
            className="text-2xl motion-preset-oscillate-sm motion-paused hover:motion-running"
            variant="pill"
            shape="pill"
          >
            View on GitHub
            <CircleArrowRight className="inline-block size-[1.5em] ml-2" />
          </Button>
        </a>
      </div>

      <!-- Tutorial 2: Shiny TDD (ShinyConf 2024) -->
      <div class="mt-16 pt-12 border-t border-foreground/10">
        <div class="pb-16">
          <Animate>
            <div class="flex items-start gap-6">
              <div>
                <a
                  href="https://jakubsobolewski.com/shinyconf2024/"
                  target="_blank"
                  class="hover:underline"
                >
                  <h3 class="text-clamp-sm uppercase leading-none">
                    Shiny Test-Driven Development
                  </h3>
                </a>
                <p class="text-muted-foreground mt-3 max-w-[55ch]">
                  ShinyConf 2024. A structured approach to testing Shiny apps:
                  inside-out unit tests, outside-in acceptance tests, and the
                  loop that connects them.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </Animate>
        </div>

        <Animate>
          <div
            class="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-[2fr_1fr] gap-8 lg:gap-16 items-start py-16 border-b border-foreground/10"
          >
            <div class="aspect-video w-full overflow-hidden rounded-lg">
              <iframe
                class="w-full h-full"
                src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/HKMhDzLRqM0?si=8UTJjBwTpGTcmyt6"
                title="Structured Approach to Testing Shiny Apps - ShinyConf 2024"
                allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share"
                allowfullscreen
              >
              </iframe>
            </div>
            <div>
              <EyebrowLabel>what you'll learn</EyebrowLabel>
              <ul
                class="text-sm text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed space-y-2"
              >
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                  <span class="text-success shrink-0">✓</span>Inside-out vs.
                  outside-in strategies
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                  <span class="text-success shrink-0">✓</span>Automate
                  acceptance criteria
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                  <span class="text-success shrink-0">✓</span>Isolate and test
                  Shiny modules
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                  <span class="text-success shrink-0">✓</span>Inject fake
                  dependencies
                </li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
        </Animate>
      </div>

      <!-- Tutorial 3: BDD -->
      <div class="mt-16 pt-12 border-t border-foreground/10">
        <div class="pb-16">
          <Animate>
            <div class="flex items-start gap-6">
              <div>
                <a
                  href="/assets/user2025.pdf"
                  target="_blank"
                  class="hover:underline"
                >
                  <h3 class="text-clamp-sm uppercase leading-none">
                    Behavior-Driven Development
                  </h3>
                </a>
                <p class="text-muted-foreground mt-3 max-w-[55ch]">
                  useR! 2025. From vague wish to working code: how to cooperate
                  with stakeholders, write Gherkin scenarios, and execute them
                  with Cucumber for R.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </Animate>
        </div>

        <Animate>
          <div
            class="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-[2fr_1fr] gap-8 lg:gap-16 items-start"
          >
            <div class="aspect-video w-full overflow-hidden rounded-lg">
              <iframe
                class="w-full h-full"
                src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/e4H28G2J05U?si=ru0yRV6LRHh7TmwI"
                title="Behavior-Driven Development Tutorial"
                allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share"
                allowfullscreen
              >
              </iframe>
            </div>
            <div>
              <EyebrowLabel>what you'll learn</EyebrowLabel>
              <ul
                class="text-sm text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed space-y-2"
              >
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                  <span class="text-success shrink-0">✓</span>BDD fundamentals
                  and why they work
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                  <span class="text-success shrink-0">✓</span>Given-When-Then
                  scenario structure
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                  <span class="text-success shrink-0">✓</span>Run specs with
                  Cucumber for R
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                  <span class="text-success shrink-0">✓</span>Align code with
                  business language
                </li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
        </Animate>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</Section>
